# Radix Sort

## Problem

Radix Sort is a non-comparison sorting algorithm that sorts numbers digit by digit from least significant digit to most significant digit.

It uses Counting Sort to sort digits at each place value.

---

# Algorithm / Pseudo Code

BEGIN

INPUT array A
INPUT n

FIND maximum element max

INITIALIZE place = 1

WHILE max / place > 0

    CREATE count array of size 10
    CREATE output array of size n

    INITIALIZE count array to 0

    // Store frequency of digits
    FOR i = 0 TO n-1

        digit = (A[i] / place) % 10

        count[digit] = count[digit] + 1

    ENDFOR

    // Compute cumulative count
    FOR i = 1 TO 9

        count[i] = count[i] + count[i-1]

    ENDFOR

    // Build output array
    FOR i = n-1 TO 0

        digit = (A[i] / place) % 10

        output[count[digit]-1] = A[i]

        count[digit] = count[digit] - 1

    ENDFOR

    // Copy output into original array
    FOR i = 0 TO n-1

        A[i] = output[i]

    ENDFOR

    place = place * 10

ENDWHILE

PRINT sorted array

END

---

# Time Complexity

| Case       | Complexity     |
| ---------- | -------------- |
| Best Case  | O(d × (n + k)) |
| Worst Case | O(d × (n + k)) |

Where:

* d = number of digits
* n = number of elements
* k = range of digits (0–9)

---

# Space Complexity

O(n + k)

---

# Important Points

* Non-comparison sorting algorithm.
* Uses Counting Sort internally.
* Stable sorting algorithm.
* Efficient for integers with fixed digit size.
